[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The variance computed here is the variance of daily demand around the constant per-day forecast, which is exactly what the safety-stock formula `z * sqrt(lead_time) * sigma_daily` consumes. That is correct.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The MASE-vs-MAPE comment is true but it pertains to forecast accuracy reporting, not to safety-stock variance estimation. A learner could read the comment as suggesting that the `residuals` list is the input to a MASE/MAPE calculation, when in fact it is the input to the std-dev calculation that feeds the reorder point. The two are distinct.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Fix:** Reword the comment to separate the two concerns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Residual standard deviation against the constant forecast.
